In fact, Republican lawyers have identified only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the rate of participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws from 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has grown since the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced in the only year of 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the voting periods in advance, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the election, and withdraw citizens with a judicial record their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo IDs issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID card.
That's a lot more.
Students, who are considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their ID card with photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011 Republican lawmakers sponsored legislation abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures taken since 2009 have reduced the voter turnout rate in 2010 by 17 per cent compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter accounted for only 13% of state voters.
The same goes for Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of voters represented only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The attorney general of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on and they see it as a clear goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed for the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the rate of participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
