The Higgs boson decorated
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole emotion, last summer, and for cause.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing but that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it’s still not entirely certain that it’s a Higgs thing.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data released this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain.
Let's suppose it's the Higgs anyway, since the odds of being wrong seem slim, and let's see what it's all about.
In this lower world, there is a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it has, too, a law of this kind: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consists in a large way.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called farmers, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "particles of force", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the boson in Higgs would appear.
These bosons, we must emphasize here, aren't all beasts as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this specific location, somewhat like a rock launched into a pond.
From this "derangement" an electromagnetic wave is born (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus, one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, to this difference near that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for that boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a little like a frozen pond whose only very large rock could ride the surface.
That’s why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN’s – the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometer ring! – to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles, nor all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while others (like the photon, hold) don’t.
Now, what can they “bring in” all this research, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to examine any gap between MS observations and predictions.
In fact, there are many who wish to be found, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and close some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (re-oops!).
But no such differences have been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The impact of these researches on the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-World, they are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no such research.
Keep in mind: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution that their work was about to trigger.
They were looking for scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already been told by physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, though not at all its original intention, now serves as a "look" at all the digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
