A Constitution for Forceps in Egypt
This is a new poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its go-all.
Taking everyone to court, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given two more months to this Assembly to complete its work.
It has been almost two years since Egypt relied on a provisional text, several times amended which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "teach his word" and "preach the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time obliging the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the challenge rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably, as he said in an interview with U.S. weekly Time.
As much as this use of an early vote holds the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Whether you vote for my text or I keep the full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, largely Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had knocked on the door, considering they could not assert their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the required quorum, 11 people, replacement members, were added in a hurry, yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles have been voted on.
Some commentators have also enjoyed the fact that one of the only differences of the day has been expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the constituent’s pendulum was misplaced.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Objections of all attention, Article 2 remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the principal source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the “establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace “principles” with “rules”, which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", the Liberals reply, which sees only one shot of communication.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular as regards the verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is alarming because "people called upon to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of liberals are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system", says Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms employed borrow from the religious vocabulary.
Reference is made to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question might in the future be how competent the civil judges are to decide on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the military's wishes, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
No longer will the trials of civilians be banned in military courts, as demanded by human rights associations.
The latter also share their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticide.
Blasphemy crime is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, in particular, the press.
In addition, there is no longer any issue of women’s protection, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will parade them on Saturday.
