While MPs and human rights activists are arguing over what the law will give for the mandatory language test, fraudsters selling “false” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to undergo a Russian examination.
At the moment, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, private services and retail sector.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
It will be necessary to validate his linguistic knowledge in Russian in order to obtain and renew his work permit.
Only citizens of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or diplomas of education prior to the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Profit, Negative Attitude and Protection of Rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Russian Language Institute Pouchkine, the University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass examinations in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what is it going to give?
What is the obligation to know Russian will change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service say, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to cross over dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for months without food and between 12 and 12 hours of paper.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
“With them, they are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they take their passports, and they don’t touch the intended salary,” said Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of the Tajikistan Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to earn money in Russia trust that they know not only the language of the country in which they wish to travel, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow would be a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have anything to feed their children without talking about properly dressing them and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people start making money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and fainted."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language-related law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work afterwards.
Yet, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, one can get a false record quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
“They ask us 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea,” Oumed Khouchkadamov, a Tajikistani national, told reporters.
“Make haste, do not be lazy, and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it was found that the registration papers of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Counterfeit papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for anything: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the examination task had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Representatives of the government and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper boots".
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the exam at first time to follow language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered a job in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
