Poland and the Cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of agency projects.
The road from Poland to space, however, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The development of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a major proponent of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many works devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a proponent of world-renowned astronomy, his contribution was particularly rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
In 1925, a drizzle was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the drizzle.
The only known information about this drain is that of the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the documents that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research stopped.
In 1937, the plans for a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpedoa powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzy.
These two projects aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautze).
For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problem, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronaut Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the international Astronaut Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, two-stage tests of the RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of engines was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
The entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later are still to be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
