The movie Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters composed of Islamist students attacked the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, even aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempted release of hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States aroused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated peripheries, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rock-and-roll cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team who came to make footage for the shooting of a science-fiction feature film.
Combination of genres
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines took note of this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is on the part of a realistically designed political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful hit, a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's Eleven, Twelve and Thirteen.
The ambiences follow: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been retranscripted in the film, there are no major differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has successfully restarted his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected stage director and his acting game ceased to evoke ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman " Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It is also the first Affleck film not to take place in its original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a story page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in the Bazaar of Tehran).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered only a few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
It turns out very well, it sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of a crisis at Tehran airport is dismissed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway is quite shot by the shooters).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it shows itself with moderate interest, appreciating the 1970s production and retro style.
He leads the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story yet, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the matter.
