The architects of the MVRDV cabinet prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince yourself, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected book mountain - 2 photos
“I think this building is fun, it’s very futuristic, finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the street’s side.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large neighboring company, tells us, “Yes, it’s really nice, this building.”
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes to one of these rigged libraries at all, right?
Spijkenisse, a charming city that has nothing to do with the doors of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls displays the lowest rate of education in the Netherlands.
In order to give some neurons back to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back on the statistics: building a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam MVRDV office of architects, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mind-blowing and often cynic buildings, accepted the project with his usual phragm and presented himself at the competition in 2003 with five pounds under the arm and a wink on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking, puzzled and raising their shoulders, Maas, the embattled, stacked his choice books in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments by a: "common dear!"
Here is my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain collapsed.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and some Mitoyen buildings and houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is how this small, tender town, which to this day had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall with a loudness, whose white fa<0xC3><0xA7>ades invite to think that they house a dairy, has enriched itself with an architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open up to you as you browse the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the floor in Dutch bricks and elegant reverberators speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public banks, dogs and little boys and little girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library beams are located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Maas.
We have completely altered the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been neatly furnished: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black ray of the library, which are sometimes lambries, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes of one millimeter thick have been used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields for years.
It's cheap and you save time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us an amazing view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and potted figs.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is located under a glass bell, the sun only lights up the interior for a short time, even on beautiful weather days.
The thick wooden beams mounted across from the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve as a sunblock, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds charge for the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even described the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “finally found soul.”
A few weeks ago, in fact, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library which was not yet fully furnished (today, it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For the architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library."
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s just for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline that is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
