Syphilis and blennorrage often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men results in at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhage and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, however, some 20% of new HIV infections are seen in this group.
In young people, a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections was observed than in other population groups.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
