For four euros, carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by carrying the sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but worn-out bearers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, at a turtle’s pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents euros for each kilo of sulfur extracted.
