The UNASUR Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public.
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 delegates present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the closing of the summit, and then posted it on the Internet.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been exposed by Peru’s president, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
Journalists' access to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among journalists was given by the press attachés of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some confusion among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who claimed more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American Arab Country Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although it had been requested by the press, it had not issued the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published in March last year.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited as much as possible the obtaining of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague that cuts a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebasti<0xC3><0xA1>n Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima has attempted against Santiago and that begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing today before this international court,” President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country respectful of international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts,” President Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era added, handing a hand to President Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international court, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chavez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
He read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been established between South American countries for a total investment of $17 million.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve drug accessibility, access to the Internet at low prices across South America", and to jointly and effectively assess the risks posed by drug trafficking.
With a Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although it did not provide the most extensive details.
The final document also mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that this country’s electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and in good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on the following Saturday in Mexico to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We are going to revise all these avenues, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will require a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will address this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the country’s new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc's Defence Ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Plan of Action, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
