Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a ruthless, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for the "Dallas" production house, Warner Bros.
"Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved the most," the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said her press attachment, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and he will miss me a lot.
“He was an exceptional person and he was living life to the full,” Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed hepatic cirrhosis at Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary type in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971–72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in cinema, he has received critical acclaim in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully hateful J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their loved ones was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", invented to entertain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman is almost murdered, has generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Through this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had brought together 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who had shot at her.
J.R. had put her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave town, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: an dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to intern his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
“I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R.,” Hagman said in 1988.
One should write, "Here's the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
Here's the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled this Friday of Hagman as "a huge man, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were released a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already completed for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel reported.
