A course on the “End of the World” has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charme decided to give a lecture on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hook there: the end of the "great countdown" of the Mayan calendar, December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax gulf some have dubbed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of late times would think it would be.
“I didn’t realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Charme told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we told it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give lessons on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the “Media, Culture and End of the World” course.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas have proliferated over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World".
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn’t go away,” said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students with no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have proven to be quite popular.
“It was complete in two hours,” said Restall about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I’m fascinated to see what people are capable of doing to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Infirmary, claims to have seen all the apocalyptic films.
“I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a teacher, told us to believe in the end date of December 21st.
“Our first project was about the Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old last-year student at Temple, originally from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I admit that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has led to a rise in these speculations.
“In other parts of the world, people don’t think about it,” he said.
This is mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew there were courses here on "the end of the world".
“The Philippines are not participating in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately begin to think about the next date" or to philosophize about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a world at the end of the seven-year period.
Students and professors take the date lightly.
Several told us that they were thinking of going to “end of the world” parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh at them together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
